<div class="col-half left">
    <p>Now Step 5 will prompt your team to help your schools format this material into a plan. Although there are many ways to format an EOP, EOP ASSIST will guide your team to create a plan with the following sections: (1)&nbsp;<a href="#" class="bt" title="The Basic Plan section of the school EOP provides an overview of the school’s approach to emergency operations. Although the Basic Plan section guides the development of the more operationally oriented annexes, its primary audiences consist of the school,">Basic Plan</a>, (2)&nbsp;<a href="#" class="bt" title="The Functional Annexes section details the goals, objectives, and courses of action of functions (e.g., evacuation, lockdown, recovery) that apply across multiple threats or hazards. Functional annexes set forth how the school manages a function before, d">Functional Annexes,</a>&nbsp;and (3)&nbsp;<a href="#" class="bt" title="The Threat- and Hazard-Specific Annexes section specifies the goals, objectives, and courses of action that a school will follow to address a particular type of threat or hazard (e.g., hurricane, active shooter). Threat- and hazard-specific annexes, like ">Threat- and Hazard-Specific Annexes.</a></p>
	
    <p><strong>Develop the Basic Plan and Revise the Formatted Draft </strong></p>
<p>At this stage, school core planning teams have already developed the content and framework for the threat- and hazard-specific and functional annexes. You will need to work with schools to revise the formatted plan according to writing conventions, provide comments along the way, and help facilitate connections between school core planning teams and stakeholders. In addition, school core planning teams will need to draft the Basic Plan section. You will also need to work with schools to create an exercise program and establish a process for plan review and revisions. </p>
<p><strong>Review the Plan for Quality and Approve and Share the Plan</strong> <br>
  After school core planning teams have finished preparing their draft EOPs, your team will develop a framework for reviewing and approving the plans. Then, you will&nbsp;<a href="#" class="bt" title="Note: Planning teams have to review each school EOP two different times in the six step planning process, in Step 5 and Step 6. Here, in Step 5, teams will review drafts of plans. In Step 6, teams will need to regularly review the published plans as part of regular plan updating and maintenance. These two types of reviews should not be confused with one another.">review</a>&nbsp; exported versions of school EOPs using the&nbsp;<a href="<?php echo base_url(); ?>report" id="reportManagementLink2">My EOP</a>&nbsp;feature of EOP ASSIST. After draft plans are reviewed and revised, your school planning teams must obtain official approval from district leadership. Your role is to share the approved plan with community partners and additional stakeholders who may have a role in the plan.</p>
<p><strong>Outcome of Step 5</strong> <br>
  At the conclusion of Step 5, school core planning teams will have approved EOPs that are ready to be implemented at their school sites.</p>

</div>
